[#_opt_minorwood_responses]
=== Responding to Optional Minorwood

[%autowidth,cols="^,<",grid="none"]
|===
2+^| Responses to optional minorwood

h| 4m+1  | accept {tribull} asker shows KCs
h| other | decline, shows KCs beginning at 4m+2
|===

NOTE: Following an accept, it seems like the roles of asker and teller
      have been reversed.  However when asker shows KCs, it asks
      teller to count key-cards for the partnership and indicate
      the appropriate level.

=== Showing Kings when teller accepted

* Teller shows kings, even when asker showed key-cards

* Showing a king {implies} we are not missing a KC or the trump Q

* #We do not use a specific-suit-ask when teller accepted the invitation#

==== Status of trump Q is known

When teller knows the count of key-cards and the status of the trump
queen, then *TELLER* does one of:

* 5T = sign-off, missing two KCs or one KC and the
  trump Q

* 6T = sign-off, missing only one KC or the trump Q

* 5T{xplus}1 = not missing a KC or the trump Q, no side king to show

* 5T{xplus}2,3,4 = not missing a KC or the trump Q,
_ !shows! specific king, 5NT = K of T+1

[%autowidth,cols="3*^.^,<",grid="none"]
|===
| teller | asker ||

| ...    | !4D!  || optional minorwood
| !4H!   | !5C!  || 4H = accept +
             [nobr]#5C = 2 no Q#
|  ?    |   ||
|  5D   | 2+<| sign-off
| !5H!  | 2+<| all KC+Q, no side kings
|  5S   | 2+<| {S}K
| !5NT! | 2+<| {H}K, not {S}K
|  6C   | 2+<| {C}K, not {H}K, not {S}K
|  6D   | 2+<| sign-off, missing a KC or {D}Q
|===

****
In the above table, all the bids that showed specific king also
show that the partnership has all the key-cards and trump Q
****

==== Status of trump Q is unknown

Teller _asks_ for the trump queen in the usual way, but really
it is showing that teller does not have the Q.

It also _tells_ that there is at most one key-card missing, otherwise
teller would have signed off.

Without the queen, asker bids 5T which teller may raise to six if
there are no key-cards missing.

With the queen, *ASKER* chooses from:

* 5T + 1 = asks if all KC are held, with interest in side kings

* 5NT = asks if all KC are held, without interest in side kings

* 6T = not interested in grand, even if no KC are missing

[%autowidth,cols="3*^.^,<",grid="none"]
|===
| teller | asker ||

| ...  | !4D! || optional minorwood
| !4H! | !4NT! || 4H = accept,
                 [nobr]#4NT = 1 or 4#
| !5C! |  ?   || Q denier ({simto} Q ask)
|      |  5D  || no Q, teller will bid 6D if no KC are missing
|      | !5H! || has Q, asks teller to show kings if no KC are missing
|      |  5NT || has Q, asks teller to bid grand if no KC are missing
|      |  6D  || has Q, no extras for grand
|===

After 5T+1, the followups are normal except that teller bids
6T with either no side king, or when a KC is missing.

NOTE: The ambiguity of this response will not cause a problem because
      in addition to no missing key-cards, asker must need at least
      one side king.  Otherwise asker would have bid 5NT to ask if
      all KC are held.

==== When there is a spare step below 5T

If there is a spare step below five of the trump suit, then 4NT is a
sign-off and the other step below 5T is the queen denier.

